 Holmes gave an exclamation of impatience.\a147I had given a margin of half an hour,\a148 said he. \a147If that is her trap she must be making for the earlier train. I fear, Watson, that she will be past Charlington before we can possibly meet her.\a148From the instant that we passed the rise we could no longer see the vehicle, but we hastened onwards at such a pace that my sedentary life began to tell upon me, and I was compelled to fall behind. Holmes, however, was always in training, for he had inexhaustible stores of nervous energy upon which to draw. His springy step never slowed until suddenly, when he was a hundred yards in front of me, he halted, and I saw him throw up his hand with a gesture of grief and despair. At the same instant an empty dog-cart, the horse cantering, the reins trailing, appeared round the curve of the road and rattled swiftly towards us.\a147Too late, Watson; too late!\a148 cried Holmes, as I ran panting to his side. \a147Fool that I was not to allow for that earlier train! It\a146s abduction, Watson\a151 abduction. Murder. Heaven knows what. Block the road. Stop the horse. That\a146s right. Now, jump in, and let us see if I can repair the consequences of my own blunder.\a148We had sprung into the dog-cart, and Holmes, after turning the horse, gave it a sharp cut with the whip, and we flew back along the road. As we turned the curve the whole stretch of road between the Hall and the heath was opened up. I grasped Holmes\a146s arm.\a147That\a146s the man!\a148 I gasped.A solitary cyclist was coming towards us. His head was down and his shoulders rounded as he put every ounce of energy that he possessed on to the pedals. He was flying like a racer. Suddenly he raised his bearded face, saw us close to him, and pulled up, springing from his machine. That coal-black beard was in singular contrast to the pallor of his face, and his eyes were as bright as if he had a fever. He stared at us and at the dog-cart. Then a look of amazement came over his face.\a147Halloa. Stop there!\a148 he shouted, holding his bicycle to block our road. \a147Where did you get that dog-cart. Pull up, man!\a148 he yelled, drawing a pistol from his side pocket. \a147Pull up, I say, or, by George, I\a146ll put a bullet into your horse.\a148Holmes threw the reins into my lap and sprang down from the cart.\a147You\a146re the man we want to see. Where is Miss Violet Smith?\a148 he said, in his quick, clear way.\a147That\a146s what I am asking you. You\a146re in her dog-cart. You ought to know where she is.\a148\a147We met the dog-cart on the road. There was no one in it. We drove back to help the young lady.\a148\a147Good Lord. Good Lord! what shall I do?\a148 cried the stranger, in an ecstasy of despair. \a147They\a146ve got her, that hellhound Woodley and the blackguard parson. Come, man, come, if you really are her friend. Stand by me and we\a146ll save her, if I have to leave my carcass in Charlington Wood.\a148He ran distractedly, his pistol in his hand, towards a gap in the hedge. Holmes followed him, and I, leaving the horse grazing beside the road, followed Holmes.\a147This is where they came through,\a148 said he, pointing to the marks of several feet upon the muddy path. \a147Halloa. Stop a minute. Who\a146s this in the bush?\a148It was a young fellow about seventeen, dressed like an ostler, with leather cords and gaiters. He lay upon his back, his knees drawn up, a terrible cut upon his head. He was insensible, but alive. A glance at his wound told me that it had not penetrated the bone.\a147That\a146s Peter, the groom,\a148 cried the stranger. \a147He drove her. The beasts have pulled him off and clubbed him. Let him lie; we can\a146t do him any good, but we may save her from the worst fate that can befall a woman.\a148We ran frantically down the path, which wound among the trees. We had reached the shrubbery which surrounded the house when Holmes pulled up.\a147They didn\a146t go to the house. Here are their marks on the left\a151 here, beside the laurel bushes. Ah, I said so!\a148As he spoke a woman\a146s shrill scream\a151 a scream which vibrated with a frenzy of horror\a151 burst from the thick green clump of bushes in front of us. It ended suddenly on its highest note with a choke and a gurgle.\a147This way. This way. They are in the bowling alley,\a148 cried the stranger, darting through the bushes. \a147Ah, the cowardly dogs. Follow me, gentlemen. Too late! too late! by the living Jingo!\a148We had broken suddenly into a lovely glade of greensward surrounded by ancient trees. On the farther side of it, under the shadow of a mighty oak, there stood a singular group of three people. One was a woman, our client, drooping and faint, a handkerchief round her mouth. Opposite her stood a brutal, heavy-faced, red-moustached young man, his gaitered legs parted wide, one arm akimbo, the other waving a riding-crop, his whole attitude suggestive of triumphant bravado. Between them an elderly, grey-bearded man, wearing a short surplice over a light tweed suit, had evidently just completed the wedding service, for he pocketed his prayer-book as we appeared and slapped the sinister bridegroom upon the back in jovial congratulation.\a147They\a146re married!\a148 I gasped.\a147Come on!\a148 cried our guide; \a147come on!. He rushed across the glade, Holmes and I at his heels. As we approached, the lady staggered against the trunk of the tree for support. Williamson, the ex-clergyman, bowed to us with mock politeness, and the bully Woodley advanced with a shout of brutal and exultant laughter.\a147You can take your beard off, Bob,\a148 said he. \a147I know you right enough. Well, you and your pals have just come in time for me to be able to introduce you to Mrs. Woodley.\a148Our guide\a146s answer was a singular one. He snatched off the dark beard which had disguised him and threw it on the ground, disclosing a long, sallow, clean-shaven face below it. Then he raised his revolver and covered the young ruffian, who was advancing upon him with his dangerous riding-crop swinging in his hand.\a147Yes,\a148 said our ally, \a147I \iam\i Bob Carruthers, and I\a146ll see this woman righted if I have to swing for it. I told you what I\a146d do if you molested her, and, by the Lord, I\a146ll be as good as my word!\a148\a147You\a146re too late. She\a146s my wife!\a148\a147No, she\a146s your widow.\a148His revolver cracked, and I saw the blood spurt from the front of Woodley\a146s waistcoat. He spun round with a scream and fell upon his back, his hideous red face turning suddenly to a dreadful mottled pallor. The old man, still clad in his surplice, burst into such a string of foul oaths as I have never heard, and pulled out a revolver of his own, but before he could raise it he was looking down the barrel of Holmes\a146s weapon.\a147Enough of this,\a148 said my friend, coldly. \a147Drop that pistol! Watson, pick it up. Hold it to his head. Thank you. You, Carruthers, give me that revolver. We\a146ll have no more violence. Come, hand it over!\a148\a147Who are you, then?\a148\a147My name is Sherlock Holmes.\a148\a147Good Lord!\a148\a147You have heard of me, I see. I will represent the official police until their arrival. Here, you!\a148 he shouted to a frightened groom who had appeared at the edge of the glade. \a147Come here. Take this note as hard as you can ride to Farnham.\a148 He scribbled a few words upon a leaf from his note-book. \a147Give it to the superintendent at the police-station. Until he comes I must detain you all under my personal custody.\a148The strong, masterful personality of Holmes dominated the tragic scene, and all were equally puppets in his hands. Williamson and Carruthers found themselves carrying the wounded Woodley into the house, and I gave my arm to the frightened girl. The injured man was laid on his bed, and at Holmes\a146s request I examined him. I carried my report to where he sat in the old tapestry-hung dining-room with his two prisoners before him.\a147He will live,\a148 said I.\a147What!\a148 cried Carruthers, springing out of his chair. \a147I\a146ll go upstairs and finish him first. Do you tell me that that girl, that angel, is to be tied to Roaring Jack Woodley for life?\a148\a147You need not concern yourself about that,\a148 said Holmes. \a147There are two very good reasons why she should under no circumstances be his wife. In the first place, we are very safe in questioning Mr. Williamson\a146s right to solemnize a marriage.\a148\a147I have been ordained,\a148 cried the old rascal.\a147And also unfrocked.\a148\a147Once a clergyman, always a clergyman.\a148\a147I think not. How about the license?\a148\a147We had a license for the marriage. I have it here in my pocket.\a148\a147Then you got it by a trick. But in any case a forced marriage is no marriage, but it is a very serious felony, as you will discover before you have finished. You\a146ll have time to think the point out during the next ten years or so, unless I am mistaken. As to you, Carruthers, you would have done better to keep your pistol in your pocket.\a148\a147I begin to think so, Mr. Holmes; but when I thought of all the precaution I had taken to shield this girl\a151 for I loved her, Mr. Holmes, and it is the only time that ever I knew what love was\a151 it fairly drove me mad to think that she was in the power of the greatest brute and bully in South Africa, a man whose name is a holy terror from Kimberley to Johannesburg. Why, Mr. Holmes, you\a146ll hardly believe it, but ever since that girl has been in my employment I never once let her go past this house, where I knew these rascals were lurking, without following her on my bicycle just to see that she came to no harm. I kept my distance from her, and I wore a beard so that she should not recognise me, for she is a good and high-spirited girl, and she wouldn\a146t have stayed in my employment long if she had thought that I was following her about the country roads.\a148\a147Why didn\a146t you tell her of her danger?\a148\a147Because then, again, she would have left me, and I couldn\a146t bear to face that. Even if she couldn\a146t love me it was a great deal to me just to see her dainty form about the house, and to hear the sound of her voice.\a148\a147Well,\a148 said I, \a147you call that love, Mr. Carruthers, but I should call it selfishness.\a148\a147Maybe the two things go together. Anyhow, I couldn\a146t let her go. Besides, with this crowd about, it was well that she should have someone near to look after her. Then when the cable came I knew they were bound to make a move.\a148\a147What cable?\a148Carruthers took a telegram from his pocket.\a147That\a146s it,\a148 said he.It was short and concise:\a151\a147The old man is dead.\a148\a147Hum!\a148 said Holmes. \a147I think I see how things worked, and I can understand how this message would, as you say, bring them to a head. But while we wait you might tell me what you can.\a148The old reprobate with the surplice burst into a volley of bad language.\a147By Heaven,\a148 said he, \a147if you squeal on us, Bob Carruthers, I\a146ll serve you as you served Jack Woodley. You can bleat about the girl to your heart\a146s content, for that\a146s your own affair, but if you round on your pals to this plain-clothes copper it will be the worst day\a146s work that ever you did.\a148\a147Your reverence need not be excited,\a148 said Holmes, lighting a cigarette. \a147The case is clear enough against you, and all I ask is a few details for my private curiosity. However, if there\a146s any difficulty in your telling me I\a146ll do the talking, and then you will see how far you have a chance of holding back your secrets. In the first place, three of you came from South Africa on this game\a151 you Williamson, you Carruthers, and Woodley.\a148\a147Lie number one,\a148 said the old man; \a147I never saw either of them until two months ago, and I have never been in Africa in my life, so you can put that in your pipe and smoke it, Mr. Busybody Holmes!\a148\a147What he says is true,\a148 said Carruthers.\a147Well, well, two of you came over. His reverence is our own home-made article. You had known Ralph Smith in South Africa. You had reason to believe he would not live long. You found out that his niece would inherit his fortune. How\a146s that\a151 eh?\a148Carruthers nodded and Williamson swore.\a147She was next-of-kin, no doubt, and you were aware that the old fellow would make no will.\a148\a147Couldn\a146t read or write,\a148 said Carruthers.\a147So you came over, the two of you, and hunted up the girl. The idea was that one of you was to marry her and the other have a share of the plunder. For some reason Woodley was chosen as the husband. Why was that?\a148\a147We played cards for her on the voyage. He won.\a148\a147I see. You got the young lady into your service, and there Woodley was to do the courting. She recognised the drunken brute that he was, and would have nothing to do with him. Meanwhile, your arrangement was rather upset by the fact that you had yourself fallen in love with the lady. You could no longer bear the idea of this ruffian owning her.\a148\a147No, by George, I couldn\a146t!\a148\a147There was a quarrel between you. He left you in a rage, and began to make his own plans independently of you.\a148\a147It strikes me, Williamson, there isn\a146t very much that we can tell this gentleman,\a148 cried Carruthers, with a bitter laugh. \a147Yes, we quarrelled, and he knocked me down. I am level with him on that, anyhow. Then I lost sight of him. That was when he picked up with this cast padre here. I found that they had set up house-keeping together at this place on the line that she had to pass for the station. I kept my eye on her after that, for I knew there was some devilry in the wind. I saw them from time to time, for I was anxious to know what they were after. Two days ago Woodley came up to my house with this cable, which showed that Ralph Smith was dead. He asked me if I would stand by the bargain. I said I would not. He asked me if I would marry the girl myself and give him a share. I said I would willingly do so, but that she would not have me. He said, \a145Let us get her married first, and after a week or two she may see things a bit different\a148. I said I would have nothing to do with violence. So he went off cursing, like the foul-mouthed blackguard that he was, and swearing that he would have her yet. She was leaving me this week-end, and I had got a trap to take her to the station, but I was so uneasy in my mind that I followed her on my bicycle. She had got a start, however, and before I could catch her the mischief was done. The first thing I knew about it was when I saw you two gentlemen driving back in her dog-cart.\a148Holmes rose and tossed the end of his cigarette into the grate. \a147I have been very obtuse, Watson,\a148 said he. \a147When in your report you said that you had seen the cyclist as you thought arrange his necktie in the shrubbery, that alone should have told me all. However, we may congratulate ourselves upon a curious and in some respects a unique case. I perceive three of the county constabulary in the drive, and I am glad to see that the little ostler is able to keep pace with them; so it is likely that neither he nor the interesting bridegroom will be permanently damaged by their morning\a146s adventures. I think, Watson, that in your medical capacity you might wait upon Miss Smith and tell her that if she is sufficiently recovered we shall be happy to escort her to her mother\a146s home. If she is not quite convalescent you will find that a hint that we were about to telegraph to a young electrician in the Midlands would probably complete the cure. As to you, Mr. Carruthers, I think that you have done what you could to make amends for your share in an evil plot. There is my card, sir, and if my evidence can be of help to you in your trial it shall be at your disposal.\a148In the whirl of our incessant activity it has often been difficult for me, as the reader has probably observed, to round off my narratives, and to give those final details which the curious might expect. Each case has been the prelude to another, and the crisis once over the actors have passed for ever out of our busy lives. I find, however, a short note at the end of my manuscripts dealing with this case, in which I have put it upon record that Miss Violet Smith did indeed inherit a large fortune, and that she is now the wife of Cyril Morton, the senior partner of Morton & Kennedy, the famous Westminster electricians. Williamson and Woodley were both tried for abduction and assault, the former getting seven years and the latter ten. Of the fate of Carruthers I have no record, but I am sure that his assault was not viewed very gravely by the Court, since Woodley had the reputation of being a most dangerous ruffian, and I think that a few months were sufficient to satisfy the demands of justice.\p\X1\BThe Priory School\B\X1\c\i\m="prio-04.png"\i\cWe have had some dramatic entrances and exits upon our small stage at Baker Street, but I cannot recollect anything more sudden and startling than the first appearance of Thorneycroft Huxtable, M.A., Ph.D., etc. His card, which seemed too small to carry the weight of his academic distinctions, preceded him by a few seconds, and then he entered himself\a151 so large, so pompous, and so dignified that he was the very embodiment of self-possession and solidity. And yet his first action when the door had closed behind him was to stagger against the table, whence he slipped down upon the floor, and there was that majestic figure prostrate and insensible upon our bearskin hearthrug.We had sprung to our feet, and for a few moments we stared in silent amazement at this ponderous piece of wreckage, which told of some sudden and fatal storm far out on the ocean of life. Then Holmes hurried with a cushion for his head and I with brandy for his lips. The heavy white face was seamed with lines of trouble, the hanging pouches under the closed eyes were leaden in colour, the loose mouth drooped dolorously at the corners, the rolling chins were unshaven. Collar and shirt bore the grime of a long journey, and the hair bristled unkempt from the well-shaped head. It was a sorely-stricken man who lay before us.\a147What is it, Watson?\a148 asked Holmes.\a147Absolute exhaustion\a151 possibly mere hunger and fatigue,\a148 said I, with my finger on the thready pulse, where the stream of life trickled thin and small.\a147Return ticket from Mackleton, in the North of England,\a148 said Holmes, drawing it from the watch-pocket. \a147It is not twelve o\a146clock yet. He has certainly been an early starter.\a148The puckered eyelids had begun to quiver, and now a pair of vacant, grey eyes looked up at us. An instant later the man had scrambled on to his feet, his face crimson with shame.\a147Forgive this weakness, Mr. Holmes; I have been a little overwrought. Thank you, if I might have a glass of milk and a biscuit I have no doubt that I should be better. I came personally, Mr. Holmes, in order to ensure that you would return with me. I feared that no telegram would convince you of the absolute urgency of the case.\a148\a147When you are quite restored\a151\a151\a148\a147I am quite well again. I cannot imagine how I came to be so weak. I wish you, Mr. Holmes, to come to Mackleton with me by the next train.\a148My friend shook his head.\a147My colleague, Dr. Watson, could tell you that we are very busy at present. I am retained in this case of the Ferrers Documents, and the Abergavenny murder is coming up for trial. Only a very important issue could call me from London at present.\a148\a147Important!. Our visitor threw up his hands. \a147Have you heard nothing of the abduction of the only son of the Duke of Holdernesse?\a148\a147What! the late Cabinet Minister?\a148\a147Exactly. We had tried to keep it out of the papers, but there was some rumour in the \iGlobe\i last night. I thought it might have reached your ears.\a148Holmes shot out his long, thin arm and picked out Volume \a147H\a148 in his encyclopaedia of reference.\a147\a160\a145Holdernesse, 6th Duke, K.G., P.C.\a146half the alphabet. \a145Baron Beverley, Earl of Carston\a146dear me, what a list. \a145Lord Lieutenant of Hallamshire since 1900. Married Edith, daughter of Sir Charles Appledore, 1888. Heir and only child, Lord Saltire. Owns about two hundred and fifty thousand acres. Minerals in Lancashire and Wales. Address: Carlton House Terrace; Holdernesse Hall, Hallamshire; Carston Castle, Bangor, Wales. Lord of the Admiralty, 1872; Chief Secretary of State for\a151. Well, well, this man is certainly one of the greatest subjects of the Crown!\a148\a147The greatest and perhaps the wealthiest. I am aware, Mr. Holmes, that you take a very high line in professional matters, and that you are prepared to work for the work\a146s sake. I may tell you, however, that his Grace has already intimated that a cheque for five thousand pounds will be handed over to the person who can tell him where his son is, and another thousand to him who can name the man, or men, who have taken him.\a148\a147It is a princely offer,\a148 said Holmes. \a147Watson, I think that we shall accompany Dr. Huxtable back to the North of England. And now, Dr. Huxtable, when you have consumed that milk you will kindly tell me what has happened, when it happened, how it happened, and, finally, what Dr. Thorneycroft Huxtable, of the Priory School, near Mackleton, has to do with the matter, and why he comes three days after an event\a151 the state of your chin gives the date\a151 to ask for my humble services.\a148Our visitor had consumed his milk and biscuits. The light had come back to his eyes and the colour to his cheeks as he set himself with great vigour and lucidity to explain the situation.\a147I must inform you, gentlemen, that the Priory is a preparatory school, of which I am the founder and principal. \iHuxtable\a146s Sidelights on Horace\i may possibly recall my name to your memories. The Priory is, without exception, the best and most select preparatory school in England. Lord Leverstoke, the Earl of Blackwater, Sir Cathcart Soames\a151 they all have entrusted their sons to me. But I felt that my school had reached its zenith when, three weeks ago, the Duke of Holdernesse sent Mr. James Wilder, his secretary, with the intimation that young Lord Saltire, ten years old, his only son and heir, was about to be committed to my charge. Little did I think that this would be the prelude to the most crushing misfortune of my life.\a147On May 1st the boy arrived, that being the beginning of the summer term. He was a charming youth, and he soon fell into our ways. I may tell you\a151 I trust that I am not indiscreet, but half-confidences are absurd in such a case\a151 that he was not entirely happy at home. It is an open secret that the Duke\a146s married life had not been a peaceful one, and the matter had ended in a separation by mutual consent, the Duchess taking up her residence in the South of France. This had occurred very shortly before, and the boy\a146s sympathies are known to have been strongly with his mother. He moped after her departure from Holdernesse Hall, and it was for this reason that the Duke desired to send him to my establishment. In a fortnight the boy was quite at home with us, and was apparently absolutely happy.\a147He was last seen on the night of May 13ththat is, the night of last Monday. His room was on the second floor, and was approached through another larger room in which two boys were sleeping. These boys saw and heard nothing, so that it is certain that young Saltire did not pass out that way. His window was open, and there is a stout ivy plant leading to the ground. We could trace no footmarks below, but it is sure that this is the only possible exit.\a147His absence was discovered at seven o\a146clock on Tuesday morning. His bed had been slept in. He had dressed himself fully before going off in his usual school suit of black Eton jacket and dark grey trousers. There were no signs that anyone had entered the room, and it is quite certain that anything in the nature of cries, or a struggle, would have been heard, since Caunter, the elder boy in the inner room, is a very light sleeper.\a147When Lord Saltire\a146s disappearance was discovered I at once called a roll of the whole establishment, boys, masters, and servants. It was then that we ascertained that Lord Saltire had not been alone in his flight. Heidegger, the German master, was missing. His room was on the second floor, at the farther end of the building, facing the same way as Lord Saltire\a146s. His bed had also been slept in; but he had apparently gone away partly dressed, since his shirt and socks were lying on the floor. He had undoubtedly let himself down by the ivy, for we could see the marks of his feet where he had landed on the lawn. His bicycle was kept in a small shed beside this lawn, and it also was gone.\a147He had been with me for two years, and came with the best references; but he was a silent, morose man, not very popular either with masters or boys. No trace could be found of the fugitives, and now on Thursday morning we are as ignorant as we were on Tuesday. Inquiry was, of course, made at once at Holdernesse Hall. It is only a few miles away, and we imagined that in some sudden attack of home-sickness he had gone back to his father; but nothing had been heard of him. The Duke is greatly agitated\a151 and as to me, you have seen yourselves the state of nervous prostration to which the suspense and the responsibility have reduced me. Mr. Holmes, if ever you put forward your full powers, I implore you to do so now, for never in your life could you have a case which is more worthy of them.\a148Sherlock Holmes had listened with the utmost intentness to the statement of the unhappy schoolmaster. His drawn brows and the deep furrow between them showed that he needed no exhortation to concentrate all his attention upon a problem which, apart from the tremendous interests involved, must appeal so directly to his love of the complex and the unusual. He now drew out his note-book and jotted down one or two memoranda.\a147You have been very remiss in not coming to me sooner,\a148 said he, severely. \a147You start me on my investigation with a very serious handicap. It is inconceivable, for example, that this ivy and this lawn would have yielded nothing to an expert observer.\a148\a147I am not to blame, Mr. Holmes. His Grace was extremely desirous to avoid all public scandal. He was afraid of his family unhappiness being dragged before the world. He has a deep horror of anything of the kind.\a148\a147But there has been some official investigation?\a148\a147Yes, sir, and it has proved most disappointing. An apparent clue was at once obtained, since a boy and a young man were reported to have been seen leaving a neighbouring station by an early train. Only last night we had news that the couple had been hunted down in Liverpool, and they prove to have no connection whatever with the matter in hand. Then it was that in my despair and disappointment, after a sleepless night, I came straight to you by the early train.\a148\a147I suppose the local investigation was relaxed while this false clue was being followed up?\a148\a147It was entirely dropped.\a148\a147So that three days have been wasted. The affair has been most deplorably handled.\a148\a147I feel it, and admit it.\a148\a147And yet the problem should be capable of ultimate solution. I shall be very happy to look into it. Have you been able to trace any connection between the missing boy and this German master?\a148\a147None at all.\a148\a147Was he in the master\a146s class?\a148\a147No; he never exchanged a word with him so far as I know.\a148\a147That is certainly very singular. Had the boy a bicycle?\a148\a147No.\a148\a147Was any other bicycle missing?\a148 \a147No.\a148\a147Is that certain?\a148\a147Quite.\a148\a147Well, now, you do not mean to seriously suggest that this German rode off upon a bicycle in the dead of the night bearing the boy in his arms?\a148\a147Certainly not.\a148\a147Then what is the theory in your mind?\a148\a147The bicycle may have been a blind. It may have been hidden somewhere and the pair gone off on foot.\a148\a147Quite so; but it seems rather an absurd blind, does it not? Were there other bicycles in this shed?\a148\a147Several.\a148\a147Would he not have hidden \ia couple\i had he desired to give the idea that they had gone off upon them?\a148\a147I suppose he would.\a148\a147Of course he would. The blind theory won\a146t do. But the incident is an admirable starting-point for an investigation. After all, a bicycle is not an easy thing to conceal or to destroy. One other question. Did anyone call to see the boy on the day before he disappeared?\a148\a147No.\a148\a147Did he get any letters?\a148\a147Yes; one letter.\a148\a147From whom?\a148\a147From his father.\a148\a147Do you open the boys\a146 letters?\a148\a147No.\a148\a147How do you know it was from the father?\a148\a147The coat of arms was on the envelope, and it was addressed in the Duke\a146s peculiar stiff hand. Besides, the Duke remembers having written.\a148\a147When had he a letter before that?\a148\a147Not for several days.\a148\a147Had he ever one from France?\a148\a147No; never.\a147You see the point of my questions, of course. Either the boy was carried off by force or he went of his own free will. In the latter case you would expect that some prompting from outside would be needed to make so young a lad do such a thing. If he has had no visitors, that prompting must have come in letters. Hence I try to find out who were his correspondents.\a148\a147I fear I cannot help you much. His only correspondent, so far as I know, was his own father.\a148\a147Who wrote to him on the very day of his disappearance. Were the relations between father and son very friendly?\a148\a147His Grace is never very friendly with anyone. He is completely immersed in large public questions, and is rather inaccessible to all ordinary emotions. But he was always kind to the boy in his own way.\a148\a147But the sympathies of the latter were with the mother?\a148\a147Yes.\a148\a147Did he say so?\a148\a147No.\a148\a147The Duke, then?\a148\a147Good heavens, no!\a148\a147Then how could you know?\a148\a147I have had some confidential talks with Mr. James Wilder, his Grace\a146s secretary. It was he who gave me the information about Lord Saltire\a146s feelings.\a148\a147I see. By the way, that last letter of the Duke\a146s\a151 was it found in the boy\a146s room after he was gone?\a148\a147No; he had taken it with him. I think, Mr. Holmes, it is time that we were leaving for Euston.\a148\a147I will order a four-wheeler. In a quarter of an hour we shall be at your service. If you are telegraphing home, Mr. Huxtable, it would be well to allow the people in your neighbourhood to imagine that the inquiry is still going on in Liverpool, or wherever else that red herring led your pack. In the meantime I will do a little quiet work at your own doors, and perhaps the scent is not so cold but that two old hounds like Watson and myself may get a sniff of it.\a148That evening found us in the cold, bracing atmosphere of the Peak country, in which Dr. Huxtable\a146s famous school is situated. It was already dark when we reached it. A card was lying on the hall table, and the butler whispered something to his master, who turned to us with agitation in every heavy feature.\a147The Duke is here,\a148 said he. \a147The Duke and Mr. Wilder are in the study. Come, gentlemen, and I will introduce you.\a148I was, of course, familiar with the pictures of the famous statesman, but the man himself was very different from his representation. He was a tall and stately person, scrupulously dressed, with a drawn, thin face, and a nose which was grotesquely curved and long. His complexion was of a dead pallor, which was more startling by contrast with a long, dwindling beard of vivid red, which flowed down over his white waistcoat, with his watch-chain gleaming through its fringe. Such was the stately presence who looked stonily at us from the centre of Dr. Huxtable\a146s hearthrug. Beside him stood a very young man, whom I understood to be Wilder, the private secretary. He was small, nervous, alert, with intelligent, light-blue eyes and mobile features. It was he who at once, in an incisive and positive tone, opened the conversation.\a147I called this morning, Dr. Huxtable, too late to prevent you from starting for London. I learned that your object was to invite Mr. Sherlock Holmes to undertake the conduct of this case. His Grace is surprised, Dr. Huxtable, that you should have taken such a step without consulting him.\a148\a147When I learned that the police had failed\a151\a151\a148\a147His Grace is by no means convinced that the police have failed.\a148\a147But surely, Mr. Wilder\a151\a151\a148\a147You are well aware, Dr. Huxtable, that his Grace is particularly anxious to avoid all public scandal. He prefers to take as few people as possible into his confidence.\a148\a147The matter can be easily remedied,\a148 said the brow-beaten doctor; \a147Mr. Sherlock Holmes can return to London by the morning train.\a148\a147Hardly that, Doctor, hardly that,\a148 said Holmes, in his blandest voice. \a147This northern air is invigorating and pleasant, so I propose to spend a few days upon your moors, and to occupy my mind as best I may. Whether I have the shelter of your roof or of the village inn is, of course, for you to decide.\a148I could see that the unfortunate doctor was in the last stage of indecision, from which he was rescued by the deep, sonorous voice of the red-bearded Duke, which boomed out like a dinner-gong.\a147I agree with Mr. Wilder, Dr. Huxtable, that you would have done wisely to consult me. But since Mr. Holmes has already been taken into your confidence, it would indeed be absurd that we should not avail ourselves of his services. Far from going to the inn, Mr. Holmes, I should be pleased if you would come and stay with me at Holdernesse Hall.\a148\a147I thank your Grace. For the purposes of my investigation I think that it would be wiser for me to remain at the scene of the mystery.\a148\a147Just as you like, Mr. Holmes. Any information which Mr. Wilder or I can give you is, of course, at your disposal.\a148\a147It will probably be necessary for me to see you at the Hall,\a148 said Holmes. \a147I would only ask you now, sir, whether you have formed any explanation in your own mind as to the mysterious disappearance of your son?\a148\a147No, sir, I have not.\a148\a147Excuse me if I allude to that which is painful to you, but I have no alternative. Do you think that the Duchess had anything to do with the matter?\a148The great Minister showed perceptible hesitation.\a147I do not think so,\a148 he said, at last.\a147The other most obvious explanation is that the child has been kidnapped for the purpose of levying ransom. You have not had any demand of the sort?\a148\a147No, sir.\a148\a147One more question, your Grace. I understand that you wrote to your son upon the day when this incident occurred.\a148\a147No; I wrote upon the day before.\a148\a147Exactly. But he received it on that day?\a148\a147Yes.\a148\a147Was there anything in your letter which might have unbalanced him or induced him to take such a step?\a148\a147No, sir, certainly not.\a148\a147Did you post that letter yourself?\a148The nobleman\a146s reply was interrupted by his secretary, who broke in with some heat.\a147His Grace is not in the habit of posting letters himself,\a148 said he. \a147This letter was laid with others upon the study table, and I myself put them in the post-bag.\a148\a147You are sure this one was among them?\a148\a147Yes; I observed it.\a148\a147How many letters did your Grace write that day?\a148\a147Twenty or thirty. I have a large correspondence. But surely this is somewhat irrelevant?\a148\a147Not entirely,\a148 said Holmes.\a147For my own part,\a148 the Duke continued, \a147I have advised the police to turn their attention to the South of France. I have already said that I do not believe that the Duchess would encourage so monstrous an action, but the lad had the most wrong-headed opinions, and it is possible that he may have fled to her, aided and abetted by this German. I think, Dr. Huxtable, that we will now return to the Hall.\a148I could see that there were other questions which Holmes would have wished to put; but the nobleman\a146s abrupt manner showed that the interview was at an end. It was evident that to his intensely aristocratic nature this discussion of his intimate family affairs with a stranger was most abhorrent, and that he feared lest every fresh question would throw a fiercer light into the discreetly shadowed corners of his ducal history.When the nobleman and his secretary had left, my friend flung himself at once with characteristic eagerness into the investigation.The boy\a146s chamber was carefully examined, and yielded nothing save the absolute conviction that it was only through the window that he could have escaped. The German master\a146s room and effects gave no further clue. In his case a trailer of ivy had given way under his weight, and we saw by the light of a lantern the mark on the lawn where his heels had come down. That one dint in the short green grass was the only material witness left of this inexplicable nocturnal flight.Sherlock Holmes left the house alone, and only returned after eleven. He had obtained a large ordnance map of the neighbourhood, and this he brought into my room, where he laid it out on the bed, and, having balanced the lamp in the middle of it, he began to smoke over it, and occasionally to point out objects of interest with the reeking amber of his pipe.\a147This case grows upon me, Watson,\a148 said he. \a147There are decidedly some points of interest in connection with it. In this early stage I want you to realize those geographical features which may have a good deal to do with our investigation.\c\i\m="prio-i.png"\i\c\a147Look at this map. This dark square is the Priory School. I\a146ll put a pin in it. Now, this line is the main road. You see that it runs east and west past the school, and you see also that there is no side road for a mile either way. If these two folk passed away by road it was \ithis\i road.\a148\a147Exactly.\a148\a147By a singular and happy chance we are able to some extent to check what passed along this road during the night in question. At this point, where my pipe is now resting, a country constable was on duty from twelve to six. It is, as you perceive, the first cross road on the east side. This man declares that he was not absent from his post for an instant, and he is positive that neither boy nor man could have gone that way unseen. I have spoken with this policeman to-night, and he appears to me to be a perfectly reliable person. That blocks this end. We have now to deal with the other. There is an inn here, the Red Bull, the landlady of which was ill. She had sent to Mackleton for a doctor, but he did not arrive until morning, being absent at another case. The people at the inn were alert all night, awaiting his coming, and one or other of them seems to have continually had an eye upon the road. They decla