hree enterprising students.\a148Holmes made no further allusion to the matter that day, though he sat lost in thought for a long time after our belated dinner. At eight in the morning he came into my room just as I finished my toilet.\a147Well, Watson,\a148 said he, \a147it is time we went down to St. Luke\a146s. Can you do without breakfast?\a148\a147Certainly.\a148\a147Soames will be in a dreadful fidget until we are able to tell him something positive.\a148\a147Have you anything positive to tell him?\a148\a147I think so.\a148\a147You have formed a conclusion?\a148\a147Yes, my dear Watson; I have solved the mystery.\a148\a147But what fresh evidence could you have got?\a148\a147Aha. It is not for nothing that I have turned myself out of bed at the untimely hour of six. I have put in two hours\a146 hard work and covered at least five miles, with something to show for it. Look at that!\a148He held out his hand. On the palm were three little pyramids of black, doughy clay.\a147Why, Holmes, you had only two yesterday!\a148\a147And one more this morning. It is a fair argument that wherever No. 3 came from is also the source of Nos. 1 and 2. Eh, Watson. Well, come along and put friend Soames out of his pain.\a148The unfortunate tutor was certainly in a state of pitiable agitation when we found him in his chambers. In a few hours the examination would commence, and he was still in the dilemma between making the facts public and allowing the culprit to compete for the valuable scholarship. He could hardly stand still, so great was his mental agitation, and he ran towards Holmes with two eager hands outstretched.\a147Thank Heaven that you have come. I feared that you had given it up in despair. What am I to do. Shall the examination proceed?\a148\a147Yes; let it proceed by all means.\a148\a147But this rascal\a151\a151?\a148\a147He shall not compete.\a148\a147You know him?\a148\a147I think so. If this matter is not to become public we 